    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Forming_Compound_Linear_Inequality_in_one_unkown">
      <title>Forming Compound Linear Inequality in one unkown.</title>

          <activity>
              <term>Work in Groups.</term>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Consider x &gt; 1 and x &lt; 6.</p></li>
                        <li> <p>Make 6 paper cut-outs and write on each cut-out numbers 1 to 6.</p></li>
                          <li><p>Arrange the numbers on the cut-outs in an ascending order.</p></li>
                          <li><p>Shade the cutouts that satisfy x &gt; 1.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Using the same cut-outs, shade the cut-outs that satisfy x &lt; 6.</p> </li>
                     <li><p>List down the numbers that satisfy x &gt; 1 and x &lt; 6.</p></li>
                </ol>
          </activity>

              <warning>
                <term>Learning Point.</term>
                    <p>
                      Two simple inequalities when combined form a compound inequality.
                    </p>
              </warning>
          
          <example>
            <title>Example 6</title>
              <p>Form a compound inequality for x &lt; 8 and x &gt; 2.</p>
                <solution>
                  <p>x &gt; 2 is the same as 2 &lt; x</p>
                    <p>Combining 2 &lt; x and x &lt; 8 gives the compound inequality 2 &lt; x &lt; 8.</p>
                </solution>
          </example>

          <example>
            <title>Example 7</title>
              <p>
                Form a compound inequality for y <m>\ge</m> 3 and y <m>\le</m> 12.
              </p>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  y <m>\ge</m> 3 is the same as 3 <m>\le</m> y.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Combining 3 <m>\le</m> y and y <m>\le</m> 12.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Gives the compound inequality 3 <m>\le</m> y <m>\le</m> 12.
                </p>
              </solution>
          </example>

